The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to jointly fight the crisis in financial markets.
More than a hundred billion dollars will be introduced into the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, the bank auctions the interest rate at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will send forty billion dollars to auction, and another twenty-four will be made available to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time that the central banks of individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This move is intended to address the economy's greatest difficulties, a growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumil of the economic Outlook Group told clients in a report.
"The coordinated action of central banks reduced the likelihood of recession in the United States from 65 percent to about fifty percent," Baumol added in his report.
