Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will also borrow more expensively to their customers.
That would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with possible impacts on the world's economic growth.
Central banks have thus decided to lower the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate, which is used for lending money in the interbank market.
