The climate on Venus is perhaps a glimpse into the future of the Earth
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus could once have been a pleasant place to live.
Data from the orbiting European station shows that the planet is even more similar to the willful twin Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the Earth's closest planetary neighbor.
These two worlds are about the same size and orbit on similar tracks, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, conditions on Venus were similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the run-down greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and lower rotational speed were sent by Venus along a completely different path of development.
Today, the planet is without water, the temperature on the surface is hot enough to melt lead and is ravaged by storms and hurricane winds.
The findings from the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which has been studying the planet for one year, offer a steady look at how Earth could develop in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the University of Oxford University's Department of Physics and one of the heads of the Venus Express mission said: "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different than on Earth, even though the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to compile a scenario in which Venus began, like Earth, perhaps with a habitable environment, billions of years ago."
