Labour's pain
Gordon Brown found a trap again to fall into; his way out remains the same.
Although this is customary in British political scandals, this one is not particularly spicy.
There doesn't seem to be any orders sold, no bills in a Paris hotel have been mysteriously paid, no extramarital fingers have been sucked on.
But the barricaded Gordon Brown would do without the discovery that some wealthy businessman had for four years masked the contributions of the ruling Labour Party of 650 000 pounds (1.3 million dollars) under the names of other people, and that the party had not reported it.
Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling an election and insulted British intelligence by claiming that the decision was not influenced by polls, there was hope that he would secure a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly funny President of the Liberal Democrats put it, the once-dreaded Mr Brown changed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of troubled Northern Rock bank showed weaknesses in driving and feeble judgment under fire.
Poorly thoughtful proposals to change the tax code have brought companies together against the government.
The loss of personal data in 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative miscare.
A trio of retired generals kicked off a riot in the House of Lords; they protested cuts in army spending, arguing that being commander of the armed forces was part-time work.
Now there are many-edged gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour secretary general (and their former internal discipline watchman), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr Brown is inevitably heading towards his end.
Despite this, governments can reach a tipping point beyond which they find governance difficult.
The people don't trust politicians and don't like them, but they usually displace their distrust when a new group takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and he doesn't even have to be in office for long, this is a push away: the state government is becoming punchy, ministers start doing briefings, the press is looking for bad news, and the government is becoming unfocused and defensive.
In one way, Mr Brown's position is particularly complex, because he cannot take the position of a new broomstick compared to other political leaders.
As much as he would like to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, problems with Northern Rock and the records of the tax office are linked to decisions Mr Brown made as Treasury Secretary.
And although he was not directly involved in the Blairo troubles, such as a long investigation into the financing of political parties caused by "ranks for money," voters can easily conclude that he was.
Still, Mr. Brown's difficulties are not as bad as they look.
Those rumblings aren't as terrible as the Conservatives make them.
As for Mr. Bean, no one died or been downright deceived.
And the treatment, however painful it may be, is to provide what Mr Brown's Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, firm and slightly brutal government.
The latest commotion around political donations is a good example.
Garboid Mr Abrahams, who compares his gifts with charity, says he didn't want any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but the decision was not up to him.
The laws against the anonymity of large political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has the right to know who might buy access to those who govern the country.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew about Mr. Abrahams's progress but did not know it was illegal, would certainly be thoroughly interrogated; so will Jon Mendlesohn, the main Labour money-seeker who learned of the tricky gifts in October.
But Mr. Brown is not yet involved; there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these plots, although the main part of the payments took place only after his arrival in June.
The Prime Minister has done half the job so far.
He very quickly condemned this violation of the laws by his own party, but diluted his determination by reaching for a proven tool, the commission to investigate the matter - led by the retired bishop and the judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law has been broken, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr Brown must do, such as finding the permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had none for six months, and moving forward with a real reform of political party funding.
That would require Labour, who are in tight, to cooperate with the Conservatives and perhaps even give up their special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a devoted partyman like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
The Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; he has two years to win back the electorate; and the only way to earn victory is without attackability and high competence.
