Does the crisis affect the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, naturally, the dorsal fins begin to flash excitedly around.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is withering, predators have focused on the credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts say credit card losses, if other consumer loan options get infected from subprime mortgages, could reach $99bn.
The signs of tension are clear.
The number of cases of inability to repay (with more than 30-day payment delays) and depreciated accounts (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable) is increasing.
HSBC reported last month that it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market - also because of insolvent credit card loans.
But it is still early for panic.
There are still few written-off accounts and inability to repay.
According to Moody's, the 3.89% default rate in the third quarter was almost the entire percentage point below the average.
Deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The change in U.S. personal bankruptcy laws of 2005 led to a sharp drop in the number of reported bankruptcies that make a large portion of credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of depreciation) would therefore rise regardless of whether the general terms for borrowers have deteriorated.
The sector also shows a good maturity that shows how much consumers repay monthly from their debts.
And confidence in credit card securities is solid, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr Dennis Moroney of the research firm TowerGroup predicts that their 2007 emissions will be 25% greater than last year.
Direct paths for the spread of infection between the crisis of subprime mortgages and the credit card market definitely exist: when loans for property in real estate dry up, consumers are rather indebted through credit cards.
However, credit card issuers look at cash flow rather than the values of the liability items, so falling house prices do not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They can even be beneficial for loan providers.
The motivation of consumers to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their property falls below the value of the loan; as a result, the debt on the cards is shifted up to the list of priorities to repay.
Card issuers can also respond faster and more flexibly to more tumultuous conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of rapid changes in the prices of liability items.
"It doesn't happen that one beautiful morning we just re-evaluate all the loans," says Gary Perlin, financial senior executive at Capital One.
Although the risk of an explosion in the style of subprime mortgages is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower house prices and debt reductions push America into recession, the credit card sector will face a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
