It's not Warhol's boxes
Whoever associates the terms Sweden and wooden boxes does not think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or yes?
Wooden boxes currently produced in Sweden cast dark shadows on the list of Warhol's works.
Most of his on the list of ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are falsifications.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" expressed doubts a few months ago about the authenticity of Warhol's "Brill Boxes" of 1968, the internal research of the Moderna Museet Museum in Stockholm comes with a result that brought disillusionment; the six "Brillo boxes" donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995 by its former director Pontus Hultén are copies - like most of the other "Brill boxes" of the Stockholm type, which are in the international market.
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of art and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden crates that were based on the red-blue-and-white design of the paper boxes of Brillo soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's approval - hundreds of Brillo boxes of cardboard. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but of their originals, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to produce several wooden Brillo boxes in Sweden, but these are not on display at Moderna Museet.
The witnesses of that time now speak of fifteen crates that rightly entered artistic and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned at auctions for more than 100 000 dollars.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum later falsely claimed that in 1968, approximately a hundred crates were made and displayed in Sweden, which Warhol then left him.
In fact, 105 Hultén boxes were produced in Malmö for the exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the chief conservator of the Moderna Museet, explored, in addition to the six Brillo boxes that are owned by the museum, also three Brillion boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood boards were painted with the base paint and sanded, were painted with oil white with a brush.
On the contrary, it turned out from the structure of copies from 1990 that the paint was applied without a previous primer to the painting role directly on the plywood plate - in addition, it is acrylic and not oil paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official list of Brillo boxes," said Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet, "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York comes to no other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify six crates from its exhibition collections as "exhibition material - copies."
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would address these "mijor accusations" made in the case of soap-powder boxes.
But the organization still remains in relentless silence.
